Poland to withdraw from European treaty to prevent violence against women
Poland's justice ministry said Saturday that Poland will take steps next week to withdraw from the European treaty to prevent violence against women.
Poland's right-wing government cabinet says the treaty requires schools to teach students on gender issues, trampling on the rights of students' parents.
Polish Justice Minister Joblow told reporters that the Justice Ministry, led by him, will make a request to the Ministry of Labour and the Family on Monday to begin withdrawing from the treaty.
The treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
“The treaty contains elements of the morphological nature that we think is harmful. ”
Poland's ruling Law and Justice Party and its governing coalition partners have a close alliance with the Roman Catholic Church and promote a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Duda has made hostility to gay rights a major topic during his successful re-election campaign this month.
On Friday, thousands of Poles (most of whom are women) staged a protest against the withdrawal convention in Warsaw and in a number of other cities.
Lym Pat, one of the organizers of the protest, said in a protest march in Warsaw, "The purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to legitimize domestic violence draulic."
Some protesters held banners that read "The Law and Justice Party is the hell of women."
The Law and Justice Party has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland's previous centrist government ratified the convention in 2015.
The Law and Justice government says the treaty does not respect religion and requires liberal social policy to be taught in schools.
So far, the party has not decided to withdraw from the Convention.
(According to Reuters)
