Cocosiri Tibetan antelope enters the return season - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency Xining July 25th (Reporter Wang Jinjin) reporter learned from the five beam protection station of the Cocosiri Management Office of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, and the monitoring shows that the Tibetan antelope who had previously migrated to the Chuanyai Lake area of the hinterland of Cocosiri is ending the birth of the children, and began to return the cubs to the original habitat.
Surveillance footage near the five girham protection stations shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three Tibetan antelope cubs to pass through the Qinghai-Tibet highway 3002 kilometers and the Qinghai-Tibet Railway Five Liangbei Bridge, and the Tibetan antelope has begun to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the resurgent flock accounts for a quarter to one-fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope flocks.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Biological Research Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "In the early stages of the relocation, Tibetan antelopes were at a high risk of fortina, so the number of cubs in the flock was still relatively small, and there may even be no cubs."
According to the statistics of the Cocoa Sili Management Department of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning has increased year by year, and the number of Tibetan antelopes relocating in 2019 is 4860, which is an increase of 338 compared to 2018.
"It is expected that the relocation of Tibetan antelopes will end at the beginning of September this year, and the number of Tibetan antelopes returning to the land is still expected to continue to increase."
Tibetan antelopes are protected animals at the national level.
At the end of May each year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang, Xinjiang, and Al Jinshan in Xinjiang go to Zhuomai Lake, which is located in the hinterland of Cocosiri.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert in the protection of Tibetan antelopes in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Animal Research Institute (north-level endangered animal research institute), said: "The migration of Tibetan antelopes is a female Tibetan antelope sheep after ending the birth of the cubs, and the process of returning to the habitat with the cubs has gradually returned to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and different paths."
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelope flocks, the reporter learned that the Cocosiri Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged for staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and district patrols in the main relocation area.
If it is found that a Tibetan antelope flock tries to cross the road, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control in the first time, so that the flock can safely pass through the wildlife passage, so that it can be disturbed as little as possible by human interference during the migration.
