Brazilian study shows hydroxychloroquine is not effective for the treatment of mild-precent new crown pneumonia
Recently, a Brazilian study shows that hydroxychloroquine is not effective in patients with mild neocoronavirus.
The study was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
The researchers divided the 667 patients in 55 hospitals across the country into three clinical trials; mainly compared the treatment effect of hydroxychloroquine or other antibiotics in combination with other antibiotics, the analysis of whether it could help improve the condition of mild and moderate patients with new crown pneumonia.
The results showed that hydroxychloroquine not only did not have a therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on the organ.
The study was carried out in conjunction with several authoritative hospitals in Brazil, such as the Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein (HCor), the Syrian Lebanese Hospital (Hospital Sírio-Libanês), and the Brazilian Clinical Research Network (BRICNet).
On the 25th local time, Brazilian President Bolsonaro announced the fourth negative nucleic acid test results through social media platforms.
During the infection, Bolsonaro has been taking hydroxychloroquine and has been actively promoted several times.
