APEC Member Trade Ministers Meeting Says Will Accelerate Regional Economic Recovery - Xinhua
KUALA LUMPUR, July 25 (Xinhua) -- A videoconference of the trade ministers of APEC members was held on the 25th, and the meeting pledged to work to reduce the impact of the coronavirus epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate the realization of a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was chaired by Malaysia, the organizer of this year's APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting.
The joint statement issued after the meeting said that APEC member trade ministers recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment at this challenging time to promote economic recovery.
The parties are committed to ensuring that the emergency measures taken in response to the outbreak are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, while complying with World Trade Organization rules.
In a statement, APEC member trade ministers pledged to strengthen cooperation to facilitate the flow of necessary goods and services, promote connectivity by strengthening supply chain resilience, and minimizing disruptions to the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products to deal with the outbreak.
APEC member Trade Ministers agreed on the need to discuss ways to reduce non-tariff barriers to trade in essential goods, reiterating their commitment to facilitating the necessary cross-border movement of people without affecting measures to stem the spread of the outbreak.
The meeting also issued a declaration on the promotion of the circulation of essential commodities.
The declaration said that the economies will ensure that their trade measures in response to the outbreak are in line with WTO regulations and commit to taking action to reduce non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion to promote the flow of goods necessary under the epidemic.
Malaysian Minister of International Trade and Industry Azmin Ali, who chaired the meeting, said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting and is progressing in an orderly manner in the formulation of the APEC cooperation vision after the year.
Malaysia agreed to hold APEC-related meetings in video format, but did not rule out the possibility of arranging entity meetings at the APEC leaders' informal meeting at the end of the year.
