Israel strengthens repeated prevention and control of the epidemic
At the beginning of the new crown pneumonia epidemic, Israel's prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the prevention and control measures, the number of new crown pneumonia diagnoses in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has taken many emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28th, the first case of new crown pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, so as to quickly take the closure of all ports of entry and exit, the suspension of non-essential industries, the change of schools to online teaching, restrictions on public transportation and non-essential social activities, the blockade of serious cities, military and police joint maintenance prevention and control measures.
This series of measures soon achieved positive results, and by mid-May, Israel's single-day new confirmed cases of coronavirus fell back to single digits.
With the control of the epidemic, all the prevention and control measures in Israel have been fully unblocked, and since June, the number of new confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia has gradually rebounded.
Especially after entering July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, the number of daily new cases in Israel has been above 1500 for eight days, and as of July 25, the number of new cases reached 916 on the same day.
As of July 25, there have been confirmed cases of 59745 in Israel, with a death toll of 448.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases broke through the number of confirmed cases, the Israeli government closed public entertainment venues such as gyms, swimming pools, bars, and nightclubs, and at the same time introduced a policy restricting public transportation, which stipulates that the number of passengers per bus can not exceed 20 people.
On the 17th, the government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of the "sealing of the city" over the weekend, and the implementation of the "Closing City" between Friday and 5th of the week.
During this time, people can go out, but venues such as shops, shopping malls, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service places such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and periods, gyms, studios and other venues will be closed, and restaurants and cafes will be banned from eating, and only takeaway services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people have not paid enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic, and have not been able to form a synergy with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After the repeated outbreak in Israel, many people took to the streets for the impact of government prevention and control measures affecting their own economic interests.
On July 11th, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti-epidemic policies affect the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of prevention and control measures such as restaurants and cafe halls and not giving compensation.
In addition, many people do not abide by the rules of wearing masks and maintaining two meters of safe social distancing when outdoor activities, and in order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on the chin or hanging on their wrists.
During the repeated epidemic, the school is a hard-hit area where the coronavirus has spread, and according to the reporter's recent visit to the kindergarten, the kindergarten teachers and students did not wear masks according to government requirements, nor did they maintain a safe two-meter social distance to each other, laying hidden dangers for a large number of teachers and students infected with the virus.
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of the expert advisory group of the Israeli National Security Council on the fight against the epidemic, believes that Israel is heading for a "dangerous situation", pointing out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and all leisure and entertainment venues and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks a master plan to fight the epidemic, and parliament and government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, agree on the fight against the epidemic, and formulate clear steps to include relevant restrictions in different departments.
